<BaseLayout title="Goalie pad thigh rise and fit checks | Goalie Gear Fit" description="Understand base pad size, thigh rise, chart gaps and knee-block verification." canonicalPath="/guides/thigh-rise-and-fit-check" {breadcrumbs} pageType="article" dateModified="2026-07-17"><Breadcrumbs items={breadcrumbs}/><article class="content"><h1>Thigh rise and physical fit checks</h1><p>Base pad size locates the knee area; thigh rise changes coverage above it. A preferred “+1” or “+2” cannot replace a sourced base-size rule.</p><section class="card"><h2>Read extension mappings honestly</h2><p>In reviewed Warrior data, a blank mapping means no reviewed extension value was published. An explicit <strong>N/A</strong> means that extension is unavailable for the tuple. Neither means zero, and neither should be guessed.</p></section><section class="card"><h2>Verify the knee block</h2><ol><li>Put on skates, pants and knee protection used in play.</li><li>Strap the pad according to its instructions and settle into stance.</li><li>Drop into butterfly several times. The knee must land securely on the block without sliding off an edge.</li><li>Check boot angle, rotation and thigh-rise interference while recovering to stance.</li></ol></section><section class="card"><h2>When to stop</h2><p>Stop and consult a qualified fitter when the chart returns a conflict, source gap, provisional tuple, or cannot-determine result; when the knee misses the block; or when model geometry changes the expected landing.</p></section><p><a href="/calculator">Return to the size calculator</a> · <a href="/methodology">How the dataset and fail-closed rules are reviewed</a></p></article></BaseLayout>
